/person/FD6E1F77-6815-4865-843C-79065810045F"><gtr:id>FD6E1F77-6815-4865-843C-79065810045F</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Alice</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Naomi</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Street</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF035780%2F1"><gtr:id>C9F2A9CB-17ED-4FCD-890B-E4F106CB2B9F</gtr:id><gtr:title>The politics of collaboration in a Papua New Guinean hospital: distributing expert knowledge, authority and agency in medical practice</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F035780/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Biomedicine is one of the Western world's major exports, and the question of how to make medical technologies and knowledge work effectively for other societies is a major concern for policy makers worldwide.&amp;nbsp; Yet social science research on hospitals in developing countries has been surprisingly limited. Melanesia has long been of interest to anthropologists due to people?s unique understandings of persons, bodies, and relationships, and their contrast with Western notions of individuality, nature, and culture.&amp;nbsp; This research is a novel attempt to understand Papua New Guinean constructs of person, illness and sociality as they articulate with biomedical practices in the Western institutions that comprise the nation?s health system. By focusing on the everyday interactions and transactions that constitute institutional biomedicine, doctoral research revealed the hospital as a site of contestation over the social recognition of different kinds of persons or agents, which takes precedence over concerns about different kinds of knowledge.&amp;nbsp; These findings therefore offer a critical challenge to dominant approaches within medical anthropology that focus on the production of meaning, explanation and knowledge. Postdoctoral research will develop further the implications of these findings for the fields of medical anthropology, science studies and the anthropology of religion, alongside policy users.
&lt;br /></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-05-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2008-04-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>76757</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The findings have been used by:
1) Academics - in anthropology, science and technology studies and medical sociology, who have cited the published articles in relationship to anthropology of bureaucracy, hospitals, institutions and Melanesia. My research introduced a focus on materiality, bureaucracy and personhood to the growing field of hospital ethnography.
2) I was invited to give presentations of my research in the department of health and the National Research Institute in Papua New Guinea, and the AusAID headquarters in Australia. In both cases they found the insights to the relationships upon which health interventions depend useful. Policy makers were particularly interested in the importance of recognition for Papua New Guinean health workers and how they might build this into health policy.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2009</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>B3A51266-EB8A-4B74-BDB9-52F675750033</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>5460bdbe34be35.19658593</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>This postdoctoral fellowship was primarily intended as an opportunity to build on and disseminate research conducted in the course of my PhD. This research examined the role of hospitals in resource-poor contexts and the ways in which doctors, patients, nurses and managers experience biomedical technologies in a place where the resources required to produce biomedical certainty are not always available.

Two key findings were taken forward by this research
1) Making people visible through bureaucratic or biomedical work is crucial to generating social recognition, and that in resource-poor contexts recognition is very important to the health functioning of institutions.
2) Biomedical technologies are 'relational technologies'. On the one hand people in Papua New Guinea understand technologies to be mobilised by social relationships and social intentions. On the other hand we can think of all technologies as embedded in relationships between people and the material world. Looking at the relational aspects of technologies is important for improving the functioning of technical health systems.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>These findings are important for health policy makers in Papua New Guinea and elsewhere who are seeking to build sustainable health infrastructures and want to know how to strengthen institutions.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>127F798F-2732-4515-876A-6E2615C466CC</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>5460bf74d9a771.09509200</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Healthcare</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>206F21C0-A4DB-490F-A876-2202BA95A386</gtr:id><gtr:title>Belief as relational action: Christianity and cultural change in Papua New Guinea</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/51521fd0c347964cac00aa8ab17fdbcd"><gtr:id>51521fd0c347964cac00aa8ab17fdbcd</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Street A</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>doi_53cfa3fa36b50f37</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>4B76CACD-3A16-4C4D-80F0-ACB72C71BF5F</gtr:id><gtr:title>Artefacts of not-knowing: the medical record, the diagnosis and the production of uncertainty in Papua New Guinean biomedicine.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Social studies of science</gtr:parentP